    { q: "In DNS, what is the specific role of an 'A Record'?", options: ["It provides an alias", "It maps a domain name (like example.com) directly to a numerical IPv4 address", "It routes email traffic", "It handles SSL encryption"], ans: 1, exp: "The 'A' stands for Address. It is the most fundamental type of DNS record." },
    { q: "What is the primary function of a 'Modem' as opposed to a 'Router'?", options: ["A modem provides Wi-Fi", "A modem modulates analog signals from the ISP into digital data the network can read; a router distributes that data to multiple local devices", "A router translates the ISP signal", "They are exactly the same device"], ans: 1, exp: "The Modem connects your house to the ISP. The Router connects your devices to the Modem." },
    { q: "In VPN technology, what does 'Split Tunneling' do?", options: ["It breaks the encryption", "It routes specific traffic through the secure VPN while allowing other traffic to access the internet directly, saving bandwidth", "It requires two passwords", "It divides the network into two subnets"], ans: 1, exp: "Split tunneling allows an employee to access a secure corporate database via VPN while simultaneously streaming music on their normal home internet." },
    { q: "Regarding Fiber Optic cables, what is the difference between Single-mode and Multi-mode?", options: ["Single-mode uses copper", "Single-mode uses a very narrow laser to send data over massive distances; Multi-mode uses LEDs to bounce multiple light beams over shorter distances", "Multi-mode is for water", "Single-mode cannot carry internet data"], ans: 1, exp: "Single-mode fiber is used for trans-oceanic and long-haul ISP links. Multi-mode is used inside server buildings." },
    { q: "Which layer of the OSI model is responsible for data encryption, decryption, and formatting (like JPEG or ASCII)?", options: ["Application Layer (7)", "Presentation Layer (6)", "Session Layer (5)", "Transport Layer (4)"], ans: 1, exp: "The Presentation Layer ensures that data is in a usable format and handles data-level encryption (like SSL/TLS)." },
    { q: "What is the primary difference between a Web 'Cache' and a Web 'Cookie'?", options: ["Cookies are hardware", "Cache stores local copies of webpage images/HTML to load them faster next time; Cookies store user-specific data like login tokens and preferences", "Cookies are viruses", "Cache stores passwords"], ans: 1, exp: "Clearing your cache fixes broken website loading. Clearing cookies logs you out of websites." },
    { q: "What are the four strict steps of the DHCP IP assignment process (known as DORA)?", options: ["Direct, Offer, Route, Accept", "Discover, Offer, Request, Acknowledge", "Domain, Origin, Record, Assign", "Detect, Organize, Reply, Allow"], ans: 1, exp: "Client Discovers server -> Server Offers IP -> Client Requests the IP -> Server Acknowledges and leases the IP." },
    { q: "What defines a 'Peer-to-Peer' (P2P) network architecture?", options: ["All devices connect to one central server", "Every computer on the network can act as both a client requesting data and a server providing data directly to others", "It uses only Bluetooth", "It requires a physical cable between exactly two PCs"], ans: 1, exp: "In P2P (like BitTorrent), there is no central server; users download pieces of files directly from each other." },
    { q: "Which protocol operates strictly on Port 443?", options: ["HTTP", "FTP", "HTTPS", "DNS"], ans: 2, exp: "Port 443 is the universally standardized port for secure, encrypted web traffic (HTTPS)." }
